article.description: The Storm broke out of a 0-7 skid against the Sacramento Monarchs, winning 86-60 on Sunday night.
article.headline: Storm beat nemesis to pull to .500
article.linkText: Storm finally solve Monarchs, who stay winless on road
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Kamila Vodichkova scored 15 points and rookie Sue
Bird had 14 points and seven assists as the Seattle Storm beat the
Sacramento Monarchs 86-60 Sunday night.

	   The Storm, with a season-high 24 assists, beat Sacramento for
the first time in eight games.

	   The Monarchs were without Yolanda Griffith, Ticha Penicheiro and
Edna Campbell. All three were sidelined by injuries.

	   "We knew they were without their best players,'' Vodichkova
said. "Even if they had played, I think we would have won. Our
effort and teamwork was great.''

	   Tangela Smith scored 14 points and Kedra Holland-Corn had 10 for
the Monarchs, who are winless in eight games on the road this
season.

	   Reserves Simone Edwards and Felicia Ragland each had 12 points
for Seattle (6-6), which was ahead by 29 at one point.

	   The Storm outrebounded Sacramento 21-7 in the first half and
36-20 for the game.

	   Ruthie Bolton and Lady Grooms added 11 points for Sacramento
(2-8).

	   "It's easy to go out there with confidence when the other team
is missing three key players,'' Monarchs' head coach Maura McHugh
said. "I think we'll keep this game in mind. We play them the last
game of the season.''
